diff:1620529602:1620529602:=1,72d0%0a%3c (:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!SignLanguage]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Similarities and differences between signed languages%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: BrandonW%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Looking at similarities and differences between ASL and BSL%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Signed languages are created not based on a country's spoken language, but based on proximity to and interaction with others using sign language. Hence, there are differences between American Sign Language (ASL) and British Sign Language (BSL). It is so different that a person using ASL would not be able to understand a person using BSL and vice versa. %0a%3c One difference is that ASL speakers use only one hand for the alphabet while BSL speakers use both hands for the alphabet. Another difference is that ASL speakers use fingerspelling, which is spelling words that don't have an designated sign, much more often than BSL speakers, who more often create signs that would be eventually use more widespread.%0a%3c Similarities are that there are many regional dialects/accents within the ASL and BSL communities. As well, all sign language speakers abide to internationally accepted signs when different sign languages users come together in international meetings.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources: https://takelessons.com/blog/2021/01/whats-the-difference-between-asl-bsl#:~:text=Just%2520like%2520ASL%252C%2520British%2520Sign,used%2520by%2520the%2520Deaf%2520community.&text=As%25